    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-11-30T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-11-30T10:00:00-05:00" n="512"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d512">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">723.00/11–3050</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Beaulac</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret   <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-11-30T10:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 30, 1950—10 a. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>398. Re <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 396, November 29 and Lima’s
                    telegram 716, November 29. Gallagher’s intransigent attitude which clearly
                    implies threat and even intention of violating Colombian Embassy Lima creates in
                    opinion this Embassy threat to peace which may require immediate action by
                        <gloss target="#t_OAS1">OAS</gloss>.</p>
                <p>Therefore without prejudice to possible tender of good offices by restricted
                    number countries possibly including Argentina as suggested by Lima this Embassy
                    believes Department should have in mind immediate action by <gloss
                        target="#t_OAS1">OAS</gloss> to bring pressure on Peru not to break
                    relations, not to violate Colombian Embassy, and not allow physical harm to come
                    to Haya as first and necessary step to peaceful settlement of problem.<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d512fn1">In telegram 180 to Bogotá, November 30, the
                        Department said in part that it questioned whether in the circumstances
                        action through the <gloss target="#t_COAS1">COAS</gloss> was appropriate or
                        legally possible. (723.00/11–3050)</note>
                </p>
                <p>From press I judge public opinion here is tending more and more toward action by
                        <gloss target="#t_OAS1">OAS</gloss>.</p>
                <p>Sent Niact 398 to Department, repeated Lima unnumbered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Beaulac</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
